    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Acute infectious nonbacterial gastroenteritis (AING) in children is a common cause of hospitalization.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "First described by Zahorsky as \"winter vomiting disease,\" it has long been assumed to be due to viral etiologies. 1 Only recent-01y with the advent of newer technologies have we been able to identify specific v~ruses in infected patients.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Most AING has been attributed to rotavirus and Norwalk-like viruses.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Other viruses, including corona virus~like particles, adenoviruses, astroviruses and caliciviruses may also cause AING. 2, 3 Diagnoses are made with the aid of electron microscopy (EM), immunoelectronmicroscopy, tissue culture, and a variety of serologic techniques including enzymelinked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) and radioimmunoassay (RIA). 4 Demonstration of the virus in stool along with serologic evidence of antibody in patients with gastroenteritis is strong evidence for a causative role of the virus.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "We know most about Norwalk-like viruses and rotaviruses.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Norwalk virus and Norwalk-like viruses ire associated with gastroenteritis, usually outside the infant age group. 5 This disease has an explosive onset, short duration (24 to 48 hours), is usually self-limited and characteristically occurs in epidemics. Symptoms include yomiting, diarrhea, nausea, abdominal cramps, low-grade fever, anorexia, headache, malaise and myalgias. Mucosal lesions of the proximal small bowel are produced by the virus.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Antibody is present in most adults, usually first appearing during late adolescence and early adult life.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "The role of antibody in immunity to reinfection is not clear.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Diagnosis is made by immunoelectronmicroscopy.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Radioimmunoassay can also be used.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Neither of these techniques is available on a routine basis in most clinical settings which makes diagnosis difficult.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Rotavirus AING is a disease of infants and young children.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "It usually occurs during cooler months in temperate climates.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "The illness is more prolonged than Norwalk-like virus AING (usually about one week) and is potentially more serious.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Rotavirus AING results in significant morbidity and mortality in third world nations and accounts for a significant number of infant hospitalizations in the United States. 6 Most children over 2 years of age have antibody. Antibody appears to be serotype specific.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "There are at least two serotypes of rotavirus that afflict humans. 3",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Symptoms include diarrhea which is usually severeand watery; vomiting and fever may accompany the diarrhea.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Severe dehydration may ensue resulting in hospitalization.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "The diagnosis of rotavirus AING is by EM of stool specimens.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "This method is not readily available in most settings. Alternatives include ELISA and RIA.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Therapy for AING, regardless of viral etiology, is fluid and electrolyte replacement.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "There is not any available antiviral therapy for these infections. Prevention depends on interrupting the fecal-oral route cycle.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Immunization against rotavirus is still in the experimental state but may be available in a few years.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "There is not yet a candidate Norwalk-virus vaccine developed.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "Acute infectious nonbacterial gastroenteritis results in high morbidity and mortality in developing nations.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        },
        {
            "text": "In the United States, it accounts for a significant number of infant hospitalizations as well as days lost from school or work.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "ACUTE INFECTIOUS NONBACTERIAL GASTROENTERITIS (AING)"
        }
    ],
